<i>grand</i> ‘big, tall’ + <i>veneor</i> ‘hunter’. Compare   Grosvenor  ."]}]},{"name":"Joyce","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Apparently from the Norman male name <i>Josce</i> (Middle English <i>Josse</i>), which in turn is from <i>Jodocus</i>, a Latinized form of a Breton name, <i>Iodoc</i>, meaning ‘lord’, borne by a 7th-century Breton saint. The name was in use in England among Breton followers of William the Conqueror. However, although this was fairly common as a male given name in the Middle Ages, it had virtually died out by the 14th century. There is evidence of its use as a girl's name from the 16th century onwards in parishes with strong Puritan links, which suggests that it may have been associated with the vocabulary word <i>joy</i>;  see  Joy .  It was strongly revived in the 19th century under the influence of popular fiction. It is borne by characters in Mrs  Henry Wood's  East Lynne (  1861 ) and  Edna Lyall's  In the Golden Days (  1885 ). Modern use may well have been influenced also by the common Irish surname derived from the medieval Norman male name.  See also  Joss ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Joyce Gravener was born about 1550, in Kingsteignton, Devon, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Aeltijen Gravener. She married William Leich about 1568, in Kingsteignton, Devon, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter."},"et":{"about 1550–":"umbes 1550–Surnud","1550–Female":"1550–Surnud","1547–1632":"1547–1632","1569–1664":"1569–1664","1572–Male":"1572–Surnud","1520–Male":"1520–Surnud","1569":"1569","1547":"1547","1632":"1632","ABT 1572":"umbes 1572","1664":"1664","1520":"1520","Abt 1568":"umbes 1568","1572":"1572","1550":"1550","about 1550":"umbes 1550","Worcestershire, England":"Worcestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Kingsteignton, Teignbridge, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Kingsteignton, Devon, I